    <item>
      <title>When random isn&#39;t random enough</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/blog/random-isnt-random/</link>
      <pubDate>Wed, 20 Aug 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/blog/random-isnt-random/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;In 2005, Steve Jobs unvailed the first iPod nano. Alongside it, Apple introduced some new features to iTunes. One of which was &amp;ldquo;Smart Shuffle&amp;rdquo;. Apple&amp;rsquo;s solution to a common iTunes complaint: the &amp;ldquo;shuffle&amp;rdquo; mode isn&amp;rsquo;t random enough. Users noticed the mode often played the same artist (or even album) back-to-back-to-back. The fix was an algorithm that weighted certain metrics like the last artist played to determine which song to play next. The result was an experience that seemed more random while mathetmatically being much less so. But users loved it. So much so, Apple adopted this Smart Shuffle as the new default shuffle mode. 20 years later and the shuffle in Apple Music uses an weighted algorithm just like before.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
